{"type":"message","id":"67b60031","parentId":"a5ce57e6","timestamp":"2026-03-28T13:45:51.657Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Evaluating git commit**\n\nI see that the commit succeeded but it included a gitlink to an embedded repo, which may not be desirable. I’m thinking maybe we could remove the embedded repo and leave the clone untracked since the user asked for a local deploy, which might be okay. However, having a mode 160000 submodule pointer could be weird. It might be better to fix this because the workspace commit should reflect the actual clone. Should I check the commit hash and run a git status to see if there are modifications?\n\n**Considering workspace repo hygiene**\n\nI think we should avoid having an embedded repo in the workspace repo unless it’s intentional. Maybe we can remove it from the git index and keep it tracked via .gitignore? But the user didn’t specifically ask for this; it’s more of an internal concern. Since we’ve already committed, a follow-up commit to remove the gitlink could be best for cleanliness, yet it would leave the cloned repo untracked. Inspecting the git status could help clarify things.","thinkingSignature":"{\"id\":\"rs_07c2f36e4998d16e0169c7db8439bc819b84243a8931b70707\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABpx9uN7UfdmZoEpBaYJM2ajc3xfbhBcjMgjCyaTQXPjsojuT8jfyMexhzYpGngHVlJLVxlSTiCtOzCIt_E0dNOwwkAY2WDaCQFJFnAU7DUDpnudIWK2d1vdnsZcc2fW2J_hdFC2LD376XnFreUSMehfZuiL0hj_Cs8jpJhGYBsAknKZkU62ftU1uaDdoq5hrnfdx3PWBHY5YvC1OuS-3fnNriC7_KnkiPWhxqAHvInUyVQLD-SfPQJz5DjHIinF0Q9P7NbOXGUSas7KYkzjzfa_g-Pn4AKsVt9kPnNAqCy9_ZZiXe7CcAF3o2mMnLOAx1qgx1kDlecLtXFMH0kgPkcqb3r1Gikn_NBFJv8NvoSPwjGKUafa624xf1jBj3kE-6MyWxg--0BaQeRMmDizyOLISm1EwTrq9EKaIusNgT7TWqqHYNd6Evt8LZKVjY2NDPC35UTGtB_YJ4DxOMpBV4DGCKUGmhqbYA7z9i4R-Auy26RuXOIPjGhQKDkDWOxwjF8ET6JARkjFha2Jh1T3bjE0yK3qUXHEjPA0GJIpOCQE477-fGbXGOiT7gmE1wAwZvyPI8m5bHa9q6B8YQx4ozrHO-DrW-YfoF59eR76raoDPT-uv99gMHnmIE1Oxkle4BFRvmWCg0s_SHT4nS4uhI8aW38